<br>
As for Wizard tactics, I believe it is extremely vital that a Wizard gauges not just the mobs he's fighting, but the effectiveness of his group members, doing the most damage is not as important as everyone surviving a fight.<br>
<br>
When there is no enchanter, a Wizard shines with root, we can pull the mob away from the melee classes and root them med... Shift targets, blast the mob their fighting, shift focus back to the rooted mob, and keep it rooted etc. This has been very effective in Skyfire and many other places.<br>
<br>
Evac, believe it or not I haven't had to use this often as of late, there were times that my group would have had to flee, but I helped manage the extras while they focus on one at a time.<br>
<br>
A Wizard can be an aggressive cleric, by eliminating the factor, which causes the need for healing quicker. A cleric converts their mana into more HP's so Tanks can stand longer to continue to do damage, while a Wizard converts their mana to damage so the healer converts less mana to Tank HP's. A Wizard can stun with significant damage, at level 53 I have 3 stuns and several spells that interrupt mobs that can cast. In the appropriate situation, a Wizard can deal significant damage using AE's.<br>
<br>
All of these comments really are moot points, since I assume most of you know how the mana/damage/heal conversion works with different classes. So I assume you know that without a mana to hp conversion, that Wizards would do more damage over the melee counterpart, because of tactical spells that allow them to effectively manage harm causing situations.<br>
<br>
I recommend to all young Wizards who haven't already done so, to print out a chart of all the spells, make specific notes about the casting time, recast, effectiveness, resistences and general nuance of each spell with certain mobs, and keep it next to you until you know them like the back of your hand. A live Wizard is an effective one.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> So the whole point to this post is what? Wizards contribute more than 2 things;</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
-Can manage mobs using root, which Wizards have several kinds.<br>
-Can stun to lessen the frequency of tanks getting hit, and to help prevent mobs from gating or healing, and even nuking.<br>
-Can snare, to prevent mobs from getting friends or taking a stroll, in fact our shackles spell last 2mins 30 secs and causes a 60% decrease in mob movement speed.<br>
-Can evacuate the group to safety, and with Harvest handy, it's less likely you'll hear &quot;not enough mana to evac&quot;.<br>
-Can nuke and eliminate the factor, which creates more cause for healing to begin with, and a smart Wizard can do so without receiving significant damage.<br>
-Can use AE's to deliver an incredible amount of damage in the appropriate situation.<br>
-Has a great self-hp buff and mana-regen spells, which over the course of a night makes the Wizard more effective.<br>
-Has the Lure line of spells, which allow Wizards to successfully damage what used to be “melee only” mobs.<br>
-Can do all of the above extremely effectively as well...<br>
<br>
I’m sure I’m missing some things, but I’m sure the point is taken by now. =p<br>
<br>
Another Note: I've been around other Wizards, good and bad ones alike, and the only comment I could add to this is, not matter what class you are, your class is only as effective as the person controlling it.<br>
